          "body": "The chapter's most underappreciated danger is not Sanballat's army but Judah's own complaint in verse 10: 'The strength of the burden bearers is failing, yet there is much rubbish; and we ourselves are unable to rebuild the wall.' This is not the voice of the enemy — it is the voice of the workers themselves, the people of Judah, arriving at the midpoint of the project when physical depletion and the sheer scale of remaining rubble have broken through their initial resolve. The 'mind to work' of verse 6 has encountered the body's limits and the math of the task. This complaint, combined with the repeated warning from Jews living near the enemy (4:12 — 'ten times' they reported the threat), creates a psychological vice: enemies threatening from outside, exhaustion spreading from inside. Nehemiah's tactical deployment (4:13) and rallying speech (4:14) address both simultaneously — the armed positioning answers the external threat while 'do not be afraid' addresses the internal collapse. The leader who sees only the external enemy and misses the internal fatigue has misread the battlefield."
