          "title": "The rallying speech — theology before tactics",
          "body": "Verse 14 records one of the finest moments of leadership in the entire Old Testament. Nehemiah sees the people's fear before he speaks. The observation is itself a leadership act — he reads the emotional condition of the community and responds to what is actually present, not to what he wishes were present. His speech has two parts in deliberate order. First, the negative command: 'Do not be afraid of them.' Second, the positive ground: 'remember the Lord who is great and awesome.' The Hebrew word for 'awesome' is *yare* — the same root as the word translated 'afraid' earlier in the verse. The antidote to fearing the enemy is a right, robust fear of God. Third, the call to action: 'fight for your brothers, your sons, your daughters, your wives and your houses.' The grammar moves from prohibition (stop fearing) to imperative memory (remember God) to imperative action (fight). The people cannot fight well for abstractions; Nehemiah grounds their courage in the concrete faces of their families standing behind the wall. Theology does not replace motivation for concrete love; it generates it."
