          "body": "The chapter's quiet hinge is verse 15: 'when our enemies heard that it was known to us, and that God had frustrated their plan, then all of us returned to the wall, each one to his work.' The verb translated 'frustrated' is *parar* — to break, annul, make void. God does not merely allow the enemy's plan to fail; He actively breaks it. The chapter does not explain how — no human counter-intelligence is credited, no battle is fought. God simply frustrates it. This verse is the theological fulcrum on which the entire chapter turns. Everything before it is threat; everything after it is reorganized work. The community's ability to return to the wall without fear rests entirely on this one reality: God has acted. Derek Kidner notes that the combination of prayer (4:9) and practical preparation (4:13) is what made the threat known — the vigilance that prayer produced meant the conspiracy could not achieve surprise. But Nehemiah credits not the intelligence network but God. The practical and the theological are inseparable, and in the moment of resolution, theology gets the final word."
